quote.p:
Subsequently, when al-Maʾmūn and his brother, Abū ʿĪsā, were sitting drinking together, Abū ʿĪsā said to the caliph, ‘There is no one like that man. Would it not be appropriate to honour him?’ Al-Maʾmūn thereupon ordered that Jibrīl should receive a million dirhams and 6,000 ass-loads (1,000 kurr
See the Glossary of Weights and Measures.
) of wheat, and that furthermore, all the possessions and properties that had been confiscated from him should be restored to him. When the caliph spoke to him, he would address him familiarly as ‘Abū ʿĪsā Jibrīl’, and he honoured him even more than his father had done. So highly was Jibrīl regarded that anyone who had been appointed to an administrative post would meet with him and pay his respects before going out to take up his new duties. The caliph treated him as though he had been his father, while his former personal physician, Jibrīl’s son-in-law Mīkhāʾīl, fell into obscurity and disregard.

